
[1]short-sightedness

   SHORT-SIGHTEDNESS, n.

   1. A defect in vision, consisting in the inability to see things at a
   distance, or at the distance to which ssight normally extends.
   Short-sightedness is owing to the too great convexity of the crystaline
   humor of the eye, by which the rays of light are brought to a focus too
   soon, that is, before they reach the retina.

   2. Defected or limited intellectual sight; inabilaty to see far into
   futurity or into things deep or abstruse.
